When I first saw the nest this evening, it was unattended. Then one crow flew in and went to the nest while another crow landed below that in the tree. The crow at the nest stayed only briefly and left, and then the second crow went up to the nest, and then a third crow came in to the nest. Two crows were together at the nest for a minute and then one left, after which the third crow settled into the nest.

Updated Apr 26: I shared one of these photos with Guy Folks and I described it as a "big" egg. He suggested Mallard egg which may be more plausible. It seemed bigger than a ping pong ball in diameter and those are roughly 1.5". This would make it too big for a dove egg. This might explain why none of the birds were squawking or why the dove wasn't putting up a fight — the crow perhaps entered the tree with the egg in beak already. There have been a pair of mallards that have been out in the middle of this same ballfield that the crow is pictured in. There is also a brood of Mallard ducklings but they have been hanging around the opposite end of the park (toward Mt. Vernon Avenue parking lot).  Original Posting: I was approaching one of the trees, aligned on the outer perimeter of one of the baseball fields, when a couple of House Sparrows abruptly flew out followed by a Mourning Dove towards the Toyota dealership. A second later, this Crow flew out in the opposite direction with a Mourning Dove egg and briefly landed on the baseball field. The odd part being that there was no agitated vocalizations going on in the tree prior to the Crow emerging with the egg.

Observation Details: Known location for the species in Palm Beach County.  The bird looks like one of our ubiquitous Fish Crows – a large, all black corvid, but the short, non-nasal “Caw” call distinguishes the species.  I took photos and recorded audio. I saw and heard the bird on the Palm Beach County side of the Canal Levee.  This was the only bird I saw or heard; none were on the Broward side.  It flew in from the north.  I later saw the bird around 1 mile to the east, as I was driving home.  The audio isn’t great, but it should be good enough to prove the observation.

Known location for the species. Photo added. A canal separates Palm Beach County from Broward County. Everything on the north side of the canal is Palm Beach County, and everything on the south side is Broward County. The bird was on the Broward County side of the canal, as was I when I took the photograph. The bird looks like a Fish Crow which is much more common in the county - a large, all black corvid. The bird wasn’t vocalizing at the time, however, there are no Fish Crows in the area, so this couldn’t have been anything else. I submitted an incidental checklist later in the day for the same location. That checklist has clear audio of an American Crow. Please see: https://ebird.org/checklist/S142610363 I have no way of knowing whether this bird is the same American Crow that I heard vocalizing later, however, there are only three American Crows in the area, so this must have been one of them.

Observation Details: Updated Apr 26: I shared one of these photos with Guy Folks and I described it as a "big" egg. He suggested Mallard egg which may be more plausible. It seemed bigger than a ping pong ball in diameter and those are roughly 1.5". This would make it too big for a dove egg. This might explain why none of the birds were squawking or why the dove wasn't putting up a fight — the crow perhaps entered the tree with the egg in beak already. There have been a pair of mallards that have been out in the middle of this same ballfield that the crow is pictured in. There is also a brood of Mallard ducklings but they have been hanging around the opposite end of the park (toward Mt. Vernon Avenue parking lot).  Original Posting: I was approaching one of the trees, aligned on the outer perimeter of one of the baseball fields, when a couple of House Sparrows abruptly flew out followed by a Mourning Dove towards the Toyota dealership. A second later, this Crow flew out in the opposite direction with a Mourning Dove egg and briefly landed on the baseball field. The odd part being that there was no agitated vocalizations going on in the tree prior to the Crow emerging with the egg.

Observation Details: I put out some bad turkey lunch meat where I ground feed birds and the crows went bonkers today. A scout came to find it, didn’t touch it, just called to others and flew off. Up to 8 came back and took turns all morning picking away at the turkey. One crow took his shreds of turkey to the birdbath to clean it off before eating it. That crow did that several times, then at least 3 other crows learned from him and started doing the same thing. They also started bringing turkey to the waterfall feature to clean it off. Fascinating to watch them all enjoying the turkey and especially using the water sources to clean off dirt.

Media notes: This is him a few hours after getting untangled.
Observation Details: I saw this crow on the ground and thought it was dead, but it wasn't. His wing was in an odd position stuck on his head cutting of some circulation to his head but still alive, but woozy. My guess is he was in a fight with some other bird and this happened. He was very calm and friendly, and thankfully I was able to free his wing, and he was in shock, and never flew. But he let me hold him with no struggle, and is still resting on the edge of the woods. I hope he survives, because if he does he will remember me as the one that freed him! (His name is Corvus, as scientific name).

Observation Details: This one landed on the low tide mudflats, by the main cove, with an object in its mouth. I walked to a closer position to figure out what it had. It was a condiment fast food container that looked to have salsa in it. It was closed and the Crow attempted to figure out how to get to the reward. It propped it up on the ground and began slamming its beak into the top like a woodpecker. It didn't seem to be working effectively so it picked it up and flew into the neighboring large drift wood/tree. It continued to pound on it like a woodpecker and then I think it must have penetrated it as it started to pull out the food. A few seconds later, it figured out how to lift the whole top (pictured) and removed it. From then on, it was taking some bites and then walking a foot away and started cleaning its beak off on the bark of the tree. It then would walk back to the container and continue.

I saw this relatively large very black bird glide to the ground of the empty lot behind the privacy fence. It made a chirping sound, and I had been hearing chipping sounds in the past week for which I was seeking an identity. "Was this the bird?" I wondered as I sneaked up to a crack in the fence with my camera. The bird was two-tone, not the same glossy black all over as crows normally are, but then it said, "Caw!" Another bird of the same description joined it and for ten minutes or more they foraged among the weeds. Later they cawed from a nearby tree and hydro line. To prove that these two-toned birds did indeed say Caw like American Crows, I made a video of one.

Known location for the species. The bird looks like a Fish Crow which is much more common in the county - a large, all black corvid, but the call was the typical, distinctive, non-nasal American Crow "Caw" call. Photos added. The bird was vocalizing while on the Broward County side of the canal. The audio proves the observation. The canal separates Palm Beach County from Broward County. Everything on the north side of the canal is Palm Beach County, and everything on the south side is Broward County. I was birding across the canal in Palm Beach County at the time of the observation – please see: https://ebird.org/checklist/S142606128 However, since this bird was clearly on the Broward County side of the canal at the time of the observation, I wanted to get a Broward County checklist in with audio, as my Broward checklist from earlier in the day with an American Crow does not include audio.

Observation Details: It was in the lower campground, and was not associating with the Common Ravens in the area. It seemed more compact and smaller overall than the ravens I'd been seeing, and I thought it was probably the same American Crow seen and photographed back on March 4 (see https://ebird.org/checklist/S130316163). But in comparing this bird with the photos of that one, it seems to be noticeably heavier-billed, especially in the first photo where the bird is in profile. After consulting with more experienced birders I'm comfortable reporting it as American Crow. One of my correspondents thinks there have been two crows reported from here, so maybe this is one of the two, and is heavier-billed than the one photographed on March 4. I did not hear this bird vocalize.

Known location for the species in Palm Beach County.  The bird looks like one of our ubiquitous Fish Crows – a large, all black corvid, but the short, non-nasal “Caw” call distinguishes the species.  I took photos and recorded audio. I saw and heard the bird on the Palm Beach County side of the Canal Levee.  This was the only bird I saw or heard; none were on the Broward side.
